<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Juncus</i> <i>nevadensis</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Achillea</i> <i>millefolium</i>, <i>Bistorta</i> <i>bistortoides</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>feta</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>leporinella</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>simulata</i>, <i>Eleocharis</i> <i>quinqueflora</i>, <i>Epilobium</i> <i>ciliatum</i>, <i>Juncus</i> <i>arcticus</i>, <i>Mimulus</i> <i>guttatus</i>, <i>Muhlenbergia</i> <i>filiformis</i>, <i>Perideridia</i> <i>parishii</i>, <i>Potentilla</i> <i>gracilis</i>, <i>Sidalcea</i> <i>reptans</i> and <i>Trifolium</i> <i>wormskioldii</i>. Emergent trees or shrubs may be present at low cover, including <i>Pinus</i> <i>contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 70 cm; cover is intermittent to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Juncus nevadensis</i> > 25% relative cover in the herbaceous layer; it dominates or co-dominates with other herbaceous species (S. Smith 1998, Potter 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Juncus nevadensis</i> has 30 - 50% relative cover with <i>Juncus arcticus</i> (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Montane to subalpine wet meadows, seeps, stream channel bars; basin fens. Soils are permanently to seasonally saturated and often peaty. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (2012 national list) recognizes <i>Juncus nevadensis</i> as a FACW plant. </div>
</div>

        
