<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Juncus nevadensis </i>is a perennial, rhizomatous rush that grows to 70 cm tall. It has terminal inflorescences with dark brown bracts and showy three-parted stigmas. Leaves are well developed and have complete cross walls, which feel like bumps when a leaf is slid between two fingers. The species is widespread above 1200 m from California to British Columbia (Brooks and Clements 2000). <br/>
<br/>
Two varieties of <i>J. nevadensis</i> have been recognized in California. <i>J. nevadensis</i> var. <i>inventus</i> is a rare variety that grows in coastal peatlands and dune swales from the North Coast of California to southern Washington. The other variety, <i>J. nevadensis</i> var. <i>nevadensis</i>, is much more common, especially in mountain meadows and streambanks (The Jepson Manual 2015). This alliance refers to stands of <i>J. nevadensis</i> var. <i>nevadensis</i> only, and thus is to restricted to the inland and montane regions where this variety is stand-forming. Stands of <i>J. nevadensis</i> var. <i>inventus</i>, if they occur, have not been documented and described within the Manual of California Vegetation to date.<br/>
<br/>
This alliance occurs in montane seeps and wet meadows that are submerged in spring and early summer and can be dry by late summer. According to Potter (2005), most stands are some distance from streams in mesic portions of meadows that are drier than those of the <i>Carex scopulorum </i>alliance, but wetter than those of the <i>Poa pratensis </i>semi-natural stands. Stands are typically dominated or co-dominated by <i>J. nevadensis</i> and may be mixed with sedges or grasses. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
