    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Juncus nevadensis</i> includes the Southern Cascades (M261D), Sierra Nevada (M261E), Modoc Plateau (M261G), and Southern California Mountains and Valleys (M262B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gb, Gh). Stands were sampled in a meadow between Little Juniper and Big Juniper Creeks northeast of Likely (Boul et al. 2021b), and in two meadows in the north of Devil's Garden (Kreb 2021).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ec, Ee, Eg-h, Ej-m, Ep-r, Et). Stands occur in mesic meadows (Potter 2005), in a basin fen at Grass Lake RNA (Beguin and Major 1975), and in wet meadows in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bh). Stands are presumed to exist in the San Bernadino Mountains based on CCH collection locations (Consortium of California Herbaria, 2017+).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Df, Dm). Stands occur in a basin fen (Cooper and Wolf 2006) and in moist to wet meadows, marshes, and channel bars (S. Smith 1998b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Juncus nevadensis </i>is palatable to livestock. S. Smith (1998b) suggested that it is sensitive to overgrazing and lowered water tables, while Potter (2005) proposed its presence indicated past grazing or other disturbance. The relatively low sample sizes of these studies and difference between authors indicate that this alliance is not common and not fully understood. However, because stands of this alliance occur in wet meadows defined by high water tables throughout the growing season, threats likely center around historic and current disturbances that have led to downcutting of streams, altering meadow hydrologic regimes and lowering water tables and water availability. These disturbances include repeat and over-grazing, as well as intensive logging and severe crown fires upstream of meadows. This alliance is also likely threatened by reduced growing season water availability due to climate change. </div>
</div>

    

    

